# AVENOR — PWA → Google Play → Apple App Store

Your stack is already right: GitHub (AbuEmron) → Vercel → PWABuilder for both stores. PWABuilder also handles your splash automation — it generates every native splash screen and icon size automatically from the manifest in this package.

## 1. Deploy the PWA (15 min)

Create a repo `avenor`, push the contents of this folder (index.html, manifest.json, sw.js, icons/), and import it into Vercel as a static site — no build command, output directory is the root. Add your custom domain when ready (Namecheap, same as VoltQuote). Once live, open the site on your phone, check the install prompt works ("Add to Home Screen"), and confirm it launches full-screen with the AVENOR splash, then works in airplane mode. Run it through Lighthouse (Chrome DevTools → Lighthouse → PWA) — it should pass installability.

## 2. Google Play via TWA (1–2 days, mostly waiting)

Go to pwabuilder.com, enter your live URL, and click Package for Stores → Android. PWABuilder builds a Trusted Web Activity package and auto-generates all splash screens and adaptive icons from manifest.json — that's the splash automation, nothing to design by hand. Download the package; it includes an `.aab` (what Play wants) and an `assetlinks.json`.

Two things you must do: first, upload that `assetlinks.json` to your site at exactly `/.well-known/assetlinks.json` (in Vercel, just add a `.well-known` folder with the file to your repo) — this is what removes the browser bar so it looks fully native. Second, when Play Console gives you the app signing SHA-256 fingerprint after upload, make sure it matches the one in assetlinks.json; PWABuilder's docs show where to swap it if Play re-signs.

Then: Play Console ($25 one-time) → create app → upload the `.aab` → fill the store listing (use icons/icon-512.png, take phone screenshots of Dashboard, Goals, Vault, and Emergency Mode — Emergency is your hero screenshot) → content rating questionnaire → submit. New developer accounts must run a closed test with 12 testers for 14 days before production access — start that clock immediately.

## 3. Apple App Store (after Play is in review)

Apple needs a paid developer account ($99/yr) and a Mac with Xcode for the final upload. PWABuilder → Package for Stores → iOS gives you a ready Xcode project that wraps your PWA in a WKWebView shell, with launch/splash screens auto-generated from the manifest colors and icon — again, automated. Open the project in Xcode, set your team/bundle ID (e.g. `cc.avenor.app`), and upload via Xcode → Archive → Distribute.

One honest warning: Apple's reviewers reject thin web wrappers more often than Google. Avenor's offline-first storage, Emergency Mode, and app shortcuts help, but if you get a 4.2 "minimal functionality" rejection, the fix is moving to Capacitor (same web code, native container, add one native feature like local notifications for renewals). Don't pre-build for that — try PWABuilder first; many PWAs pass.

## 4. Splash automation summary

Three layers, all already wired: (1) the in-app animated AVENOR splash in index.html covers web and every wrapper; (2) Android's native splash is generated by the TWA from `background_color` + `theme_color` + the 512 icon in manifest.json; (3) iOS launch screens are generated by PWABuilder's iOS packager from the same manifest. Change the brand once in manifest.json and everything downstream regenerates on the next package.

## 5. Text visibility — what changed

Secondary text darkened from #6B7283 to #555D70 (passes WCAG AA on the porcelain background), row titles now wrap instead of truncating with "…", metadata and tab labels bumped up in size, and all dim white text in Emergency Mode raised to 78–94% opacity so it reads in bright sunlight — the situation Emergency Mode exists for.

## Order of operations

1. Push this folder to GitHub → Vercel → verify install + offline on your phone.
2. PWABuilder Android package → add assetlinks.json → Play Console closed test (14-day clock).
3. While waiting: screenshots, store copy, privacy policy page (required by both stores — one paragraph stating data stays on-device is enough for v1).
4. PWABuilder iOS package → Xcode → App Store review.
5. v2: Supabase sync, then notifications — which also strengthens the Apple review case.
